Title: The Tell-Tale Heart
Credit: Written by
Author: Edgar Allan Poe
Source: Adapted from book
Draft date: 7/21/2026
Notes: Gothic period live-action; candlelit interiors; closed cast; the NARRATOR is a lean man of middle years, dark hair disheveled, pale intense eyes, plain dark waistcoat and shirtsleeves; the OLD MAN is frail, white-haired, with a pale blue vulture eye filmed over; officers in plain 1840s coats and badges.

FADE IN:

INT. NARRATOR'S CHAMBER - NIGHT

A spare, candlelit room. THE NARRATOR sits forward in a wooden chair, facing us—lean, middle-aged, dark hair disordered, pale eyes too bright. Plain dark waistcoat over shirtsleeves. He is dreadfully calm.

NARRATOR
True!—nervous—very, very dreadfully nervous I had been and am; but why will you say that I am mad? The disease had sharpened my senses—not destroyed—not dulled them. Above all was the sense of hearing acute. I heard all things in the heaven and in the earth. I heard many things in hell. How, then, am I mad? Hearken! and observe how healthily—how calmly I can tell you the whole story.

He steadies his hands on his knees.

NARRATOR (CONT'D)
It is impossible to say how first the idea entered my brain; but once conceived, it haunted me day and night. Object there was none. Passion there was none. I loved the old man. He had never wronged me. He had never given me insult. For his gold I had no desire. I think it was his eye! yes, it was this!

INT. OLD MAN'S BEDROOM - DAY

THE OLD MAN sits by a shuttered window—frail, white-haired. He turns. His left eye is pale blue, filmed, vulture-like. Light catches the film.

THE NARRATOR (at the door, younger in this memory, composed) freezes as the eye falls on him. His blood runs cold in his face.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
He had the eye of a vulture—a pale blue eye, with a film over it. Whenever it fell upon me, my blood ran cold; and so by degrees—very gradually—I made up my mind to take the life of the old man, and thus rid myself of the eye forever.

INT. NARRATOR'S CHAMBER - NIGHT

The NARRATOR leans in, almost smiling.

NARRATOR
Now this is the point. You fancy me mad. Madmen know nothing. But you should have seen me. You should have seen how wisely I proceeded—with what caution—with what foresight—with what dissimulation I went to work! I was never kinder to the old man than during the whole week before I killed him.

INT. OLD MAN'S BEDROOM - DAY

Morning light through a crack in the shutters. The NARRATOR enters boldly with a tray, hearty, kind. The OLD MAN in bed, the filmed eye half-lidded.

NARRATOR
Good morning! And how have you passed the night?

The OLD MAN murmurs a weary courtesy. The NARRATOR smiles, adjusts the blanket, leaves nothing amiss.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
Every morning, when the day broke, I went boldly into the chamber, and spoke courageously to him, calling him by name in a hearty tone, and inquiring how he has passed the night. So you see he would have been a very profound old man, indeed, to suspect...

INT. HALL OUTSIDE OLD MAN'S DOOR - NIGHT

Midnight. A dark lantern, fully closed, in the NARRATOR's hand. He turns the latch—oh, so gently—and opens the door a hair's breadth.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
And every night, about midnight, I turned the latch of his door and opened it—oh, so gently!

He eases an opening sufficient for his head. Thrusts the closed lantern in, then his head—slowly—very, very slowly.

INT. OLD MAN'S BEDROOM - NIGHT

Pitch dark. Shutters close fastened. The NARRATOR's head in the opening. He undoes the lantern cautiously—hinges creak softly—until a single thin ray falls across the bed.

The ray finds the OLD MAN asleep. The vulture eye is closed.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
It took me an hour to place my whole head within the opening so far that I could see him as he lay upon his bed. Ha!—would a madman have been so wise as this? And this I did for seven long nights—every night just at midnight—but I found the eye always closed; and so it was impossible to do the work; for it was not the old man who vexed me, but his Evil Eye.

He withdraws. The ray dies.

INT. NARRATOR'S CHAMBER - NIGHT

NARRATOR
Upon the eighth night I was more than usually cautious in opening the door. A watch's minute hand moves more quickly than did mine. Never before that night had I felt the extent of my own powers—of my sagacity.

INT. HALL OUTSIDE OLD MAN'S DOOR - NIGHT

The NARRATOR at the door again. He pushes it open little by little. A soft chuckle escapes him.

Inside: a sudden stir of bedclothes.

He does not draw back. He keeps pushing—steadily, steadily—into the thick darkness.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
I fairly chuckled at the idea; and perhaps he heard me; for he moved on the bed suddenly, as if startled. Now you may think that I drew back—but no. His room was as black as pitch with the thick darkness, for the shutters were close fastened, through fear of robbers, and so I knew that he could not see the opening of the door.

INT. OLD MAN'S BEDROOM - NIGHT

The NARRATOR's head is in. His thumb slips on the tin fastening of the lantern.

A small metallic sound.

The OLD MAN springs up in bed.

OLD MAN
Who's there?

Silence. The NARRATOR does not move a muscle. Does not breathe.

The OLD MAN sits upright in the dark, listening—listening.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
I kept quite still and said nothing. For a whole hour I did not move a muscle, and in the meantime I did not hear him lie down. He was still sitting up in the bed listening;—just as I have done, night after night, hearkening to the death watches in the wall.

Time holds. A deathwatch beetle ticks faintly in the wood.

Presently: a slight groan—low, stifled—from the bed. Not pain. Terror.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
Presently I heard a slight groan, and I knew it was the groan of mortal terror. It was not a groan of pain or of grief—oh, no!—it was the low stifled sound that arises from the bottom of the soul when overcharged with awe. I knew the sound well. I knew what the old man felt, and pitied him, although I chuckled at heart.

On the bed, the OLD MAN stares into blackness, whispering to himself.

OLD MAN
(whispered, to himself)
It is nothing but the wind in the chimney—it is only a mouse crossing the floor... It is merely a cricket which has made a single chirp.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
Yes, he had been trying to comfort himself with these suppositions: but he had found all in vain. All in vain; because Death, in approaching him had stalked with his black shadow before him, and enveloped the victim.

The NARRATOR waits—a long time—very patiently. Then, stealthily, he opens a very little crevice in the lantern.

A single dim ray, like the thread of a spider, shoots out and falls full upon the vulture eye.

It is open—wide, wide open.

The NARRATOR's face hardens to fury. The ray holds on the dull blue eye, the hideous veil. Nothing else of the face—only that damned spot.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
It was open—wide, wide open—and I grew furious as I gazed upon it. I saw it with perfect distinctness—all a dull blue, with a hideous veil over it that chilled the very marrow in my bones.

A low, dull, quick sound begins—such as a watch makes when enveloped in cotton. The beating of the OLD MAN's heart.

It quickens. Louder. The NARRATOR holds the lantern motionless. Scarcely breathes.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
And have I not told you that what you mistake for madness is but over-acuteness of the sense?—now, I say, there came to my ears a low, dull, quick sound, such as a watch makes when enveloped in cotton. I knew that sound well, too. It was the beating of the old man's heart. It increased my fury, as the beating of a drum stimulates the soldier into courage.

The hellish tattoo grows quicker and louder. The OLD MAN's terror is extreme—still sitting, rigid, in the thin ray.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
Meantime the hellish tattoo of the heart increased. It grew quicker and quicker, and louder and louder every instant. The old man's terror must have been extreme! It grew louder, I say, louder every moment!—do you mark me well?

The NARRATOR's own nerves fray. He refrains still—minutes longer—then a new anxiety seizes him.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
And now at the dead hour of the night, amid the dreadful silence of that old house, so strange a noise as this excited me to uncontrollable terror. Yet, for some minutes longer I refrained and stood still. But the beating grew louder, louder! I thought the heart must burst. And now a new anxiety seized me—the sound would be heard by a neighbour! The old man's hour had come!

With a loud yell he throws open the lantern and leaps into the room.

The OLD MAN shrieks once—once only.

In an instant the NARRATOR drags him to the floor and pulls the heavy bed over him.

The NARRATOR stands, smiling gaily in the open lantern light.

Beneath the overturned bed: the heart still beats—muffled—on and on.

He listens. Many minutes. He does not move. The muffled sound continues, then falters, then ceases.

He removes the bed. Examines the corpse. Places his hand upon the heart and holds it there—many minutes. No pulsation.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
I then smiled gaily, to find the deed so far done. But, for many minutes, the heart beat on with a muffled sound. This, however, did not vex me; it would not be heard through the wall. At length it ceased. The old man was dead. Yes, he was stone, stone dead. I placed my hand upon the heart and held it there many minutes. There was no pulsation. He was stone dead. His eye would trouble me no more.

INT. NARRATOR'S CHAMBER - NIGHT

NARRATOR
If still you think me mad, you will think so no longer when I describe the wise precautions I took for the concealment of the body.

INT. OLD MAN'S BEDROOM - NIGHT

The night wanes. The NARRATOR works hastily, in silence. A tub stands ready.

He dismembers the corpse—head, arms, legs—motions clean, wary; the tub catches all. No stain on the floor.

He pries up three planks from the flooring, deposits the remains between the scantlings, replaces the boards so cleverly that the seams lie true.

He runs a hand over the smooth floor. Nothing wrong. No blood-spot whatever.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
First of all I dismembered the corpse. I cut off the head and the arms and the legs. I then took up three planks from the flooring of the chamber, and deposited all between the scantlings. I then replaced the boards so cleverly, so cunningly, that no human eye—not even his—could have detected any thing wrong. There was nothing to wash out—no stain of any kind—no blood-spot whatever. I had been too wary for that. A tub had caught all—ha! ha!

A distant clock bell sounds four.

INT. STREET DOOR - NIGHT

Still dark as midnight. A knocking at the street door.

The NARRATOR goes down with a light heart and opens it.

Three men in plain coats: OFFICER REYNOLDS, OFFICER HALE, OFFICER BRIGGS. They introduce themselves with perfect suavity.

OFFICER REYNOLDS
A shriek was heard by a neighbour during the night. Suspicion of foul play has been aroused. We have been deputed to search the premises.

The NARRATOR smiles.

NARRATOR
Gentlemen—welcome. The shriek was my own, in a dream. The old man is absent in the country. Search—search well.

INT. HALL AND SITTING ROOM - NIGHT

Lanterns raised. The NARRATOR leads them through—cupboards, corners, passages—open, easy, almost gay.

INT. OLD MAN'S BEDROOM - NIGHT

He leads them in at last. Shows the old man's treasures—secure, undisturbed. In the enthusiasm of his confidence he brings chairs.

NARRATOR
Rest from your fatigues. Sit, gentlemen.

He places his own seat upon the very spot beneath which the corpse reposes—and sits.

The officers sit. They are satisfied. His manner has convinced them.

OFFICER HALE
A quiet house, then.

NARRATOR
Quiet as the grave. Cheerily—ask what you will.

They chat of familiar things. The NARRATOR answers cheerily—singularly at ease.

Ere long his face pales. He wishes them gone. A faint ringing in his ears.

He talks on. The ringing becomes more distinct—gains definiteness—until he knows the noise is not within his ears.

A low, dull, quick sound—such as a watch makes when enveloped in cotton.

He gasps for breath. The officers hear it not. They smile and chat on.

NARRATOR
(more quickly, vehemently)
Yes—yes—the streets are safer of late—one hears such stories—

The noise steadily increases. He rises. Argues about trifles in a high key, with violent gesticulations.

NARRATOR (CONT'D)
—and the markets! The price of flour alone—

He paces the floor with heavy strides. Foams. Raves. Swears. Grates his chair upon the boards.

The noise arises over all—louder—louder—louder.

The officers chat pleasantly and smile.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
Was it possible they heard not? Almighty God!—no, no! They heard!—they suspected!—they knew!—they were making a mockery of my horror!—this I thought, and this I think. But anything was better than this agony! Anything was more tolerable than this derision! I could bear those hypocritical smiles no longer! I felt that I must scream or die! and now—again!—hark! louder! louder! louder! louder!

He breaks—shrieking, pointing at the floor beneath his chair.

NARRATOR
Villains! dissemble no more! I admit the deed!—tear up the planks!—here, here!—It is the beating of his hideous heart!

The officers spring up. The low dull quick sound seems to fill the room.

FADE OUT.

THE END
